  {
    "objectID": "ch01_foundations/3.view-builder.html",
    "href": "ch01_foundations/3.view-builder.html",
    "title": "3  ViewBuilder",
    "section": "",
    "text": "A ViewBuilder is a property wrapper that allows you to create views that can accept multiple child views.\nstruct MyView&lt;Content: View&gt;: View {\n    let content: Content\n    \n    init(@ViewBuilder content: () -&gt; Content) {\n        self.content = content()\n    }\n    \n    var body: some View {\n        content\n    }\n}",
    "crumbs": [
      "Part I: Foundations",
      "<span class='chapter-number'>3</span>  <span class='chapter-title'>ViewBuilder</span>"
    ]
  },
  {
    "objectID": "ch01_foundations/5.view-builder.html",
    "href": "ch01_foundations/5.view-builder.html",
    "title": "5  ViewBuilder",
    "section": "",
    "text": "A (ViewBuilder?) is a list of Views. The reason for using it is to group together functional code.\n\nViewBuilder\na property wrapper that allows for lets, ifs, switches etc. within a view.\n\nfunc matchMarker(peg: Int) -&gt; some View {\n    if peg == 1 {\n        return Text(\"1\")\n    } else {\n        return Text(\"2\")\n    }\n    return Circle().fill(.red) \n}\nadding ‘(ViewBuilder?)’ to the following function transforms it to no longer need return\n\n@ViewBuilder\nfunc matchMarker(peg: Int) -&gt; some View {\n    if peg == 1 {\n        Text(\"1\")\n    } else {\n        Text(\"2\")\n    }\n    Circle().fill(.red) \n}",
    "crumbs": [
      "Part I: Foundations",
      "<span class='chapter-number'>5</span>  <span class='chapter-title'>ViewBuilder</span>"
    ]
  }
